bug.short_desc: New technology agent controller build does not exit on failure

long_desc.thetext:
The bash build scripts for the Linux build do not exit abnormally when one of the called `make' processes fails. This can be deceiving because it obscures the underlying build failure and the caller of the build script is unaware that the build failed when checking the return code.
I will attach a patch that causes the build scripts to exit abnormally at the time when one of the called `make' processes fails.

Created an attachment (id=48819) TPTP AC build exit on failure patch
2006-08-26 Jeremy Handcock <jeremy at aperte dot org>
* build/build_tptp_ac.script: Exit abnormally when `make' fails. * build/build_tptp_ac.script64: Same. * build/build_tptp_samples.script: Same.

Do you have any particular affinity for all failures returning 1? I'd prefer that I specify a different number for each stage so that in the future anyone could programmatically determine where the build failed should they so desire.
I have no attachment to the exact return code, no. As long as the build stops immediately upon failure and exits with an abnormal (non-zero) return code, that solves the issue. Thanks!

I'm polling the developers here, and the consensus so far is that they see great value in having the build continue on past the first failure. (That's the Windows build approach as well.) A counterproposal has been to continue, but either (1) count the number of failures and LOUDLY proclaim the number of component build failures when done, or (2) do 1 but also report on each component individually so that you can see which ones failed easily.
(1) is very easy, but (2) is much more convoluted, of course.
Only a third of our people are here today, so I don't expect a clear sense of the "vote" until next week.

It's a conventional thing to have a build exit immediately and abnormally upon failure when you're building a package of software. There are subdirectories with independently-invokable Makefiles in the build system, so one could always build the sub-systems independently if one so desired.
What are your thoughts around why the build should continue?

I've accommodated the idea of "not failing silently" by noting each component's build failure as it occurs and at the end of the build noting the success or number of failures and then enumerating each failed component. I've also accommodated our developers, whose consensus was that when a build failure was injected, they learned more if they didn't just fail at the first problem. Yes, there are interdependencies, but those interdependencies don't cover the whole graph (particularly for samples).
We get the count right, but the list includes everything ... ||/&& precedence problem I need to fix.
Got rid of the &&s... that should fix it.

bug.short_desc: Add optional detailed logging to PDOM parser

long_desc.thetext:
Even with the latest fixes PDOM parser misses ~80% of all classes in the large code base I'm working with. My attempts to create a small project reproducing the problem didn't succeed. When I take a .h file declaring a class missed by the parser and copy it to a separate project, it gets indexed just fine. There is some cumulative effect of the large code base that throws the parser off. The large code base that exhibits this behavior is proprietary and cannot be shared with CDT community.
In order to find out what throws the PDOM parser off I need a detailed logging in the parser that could be enabled for an individual source file and would produce a detailed trace of the parsing of that file in the context of a complete index rebuild.
Another useful kind of logging is to log every occurrence of an include statement that could not be resolved to a physical file.

I'm also interested in this as we want to ensure that the Symbian OS headers are correctly parsed when generating offline indexes.
Maybe we could do this via an optional listener interface on the indexer (i.e. IPDOMIndexer.addXXXListener()) that enabled getting hold of the IASTProblem[] returned via CPPVisitor.getProblems(IASTTranslationUnit) result

The listener idea is interesting but I don't think the logging should be limited to problems. Ideally I'd like to see a pretty detailed trace of everything PDOM parser does on a particular file. It may be easier to put this functionality in the parser itself and have it controlled through config.ini.

> functionality in the parser itself and have it controlled through config.ini.
Is this the same as specifying a trace option? I like the trace options because you can set it in the UI as a part of the launch configuration when debugging a plug-in.

If we are to do this it at all it should be using the Tracing objects. We currently use that to generate the PDOM timings.
I already have detailed logging, it's called the Java debugger :).
I meant tracing options. Need more coffee...

I have added some statistics when tracing with debug/pdomtimings. Here is a sample output: PDOMFastReindex firefox-2.0 (2426 sources, 4075 headers) PDOMFastReindex Timings: 856704 total, 838820 parser, 124829 resolution, 431671 index update. PDOMFastReindex Result: 521625 declarations, 1537279 references, 2 errors, 576105 problems.
576105 problems is alarming, isn't it?

I'm not sure I'd use the term "alarming". But it is part of the trade-off between the Fast indexer and Full indexer, and part of the reason I termed it "less accurate". Driving this towards zero definitely needs to be something we focus on once we get the architecture the way we want it, while at the same time not increasing the times back to where they were unacceptable.

576105 problems means that there are on average 89 problems per source or header file. The number of problems exceeds the number of declarations. "Alarming" doesn't seem to be a strong enough word for this.

Well, the more accurate way to judge this is to add the declarations and references and problems together to get the number of names we found (candidates for PDOM). Then compare the number of problems to that. With Markus's numbers here we are missing only 22% of the names. Which is not too bad given the crazy heuristics we're using to make the PDOM indexer so fast.

My day-to-day experience of using CDT is quite different from a rosy 78% coverage picture. After the latest changes most declarations get into the index, but most definitions still don't. It's hard to judge the quality of references since References command virtually never works.
Agreed. Again, driving the number of problems down should make things better, but it will take time. Good thing we have 7 months before the release of 4.0.
Should the parser log code fragments around locations of problems so that somebody could recognise some patterns by looking at them?

I have added another tracing option to output problem locations. I have also consolidated the option names:
org.eclipse.cdt.core/debug/indexer/activity: Outputs files indexed. org.eclipse.cdt.core/debug/indexer/statistics: Reports statistics. org.eclipse.cdt.core/debug/indexer/problems: Outputs problem locations.
From my point of view this completes tracing for the indexer.
Agreed. I'll mark this fixed. If there is anything more, we can add it as we go.

bug.short_desc: Support auto expansion rules for Variables view

long_desc.thetext:
Some types, like std::string, may have a complex internal structure, but a simple meaning. Having to open multiple levels of node hierarchy to see the contents of a string is very annoying. In most cases user does not care about all details of the string object and just wants to see the contents of the string. MS Visual Studio solves this problem by supporting user-defined auto expansion rules. CDT should support similar rules, so that users could customize display of frequently used types.
The syntax used to define auto expansion rules in MS Visual Studio is described in http://www.codeguru.com/Cpp/V-S/debug/article.php/c1281/#StructureExpand
CDT would also benefit from another useful MSVC feature described in the same article: http://www.codeguru.com/Cpp/V-S/debug/article.php/c1281/#NoStepInto.

I don't think that this bug really depends on 131931. Auto expansion rules in MSVS sense are about custom, type specific, display of variables, not about opening the existing tree to a deeper level. I would even argue that this bug and bug 150470 provide a superior alternative to 131931.

long_desc.thetext:

Example is below: <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <xsd:schema xmlns:_2="http://www.fpml.org/2005/FpML-4-2" xmlns:ecore="http://www.eclipse.org/emf/2002/Ecore" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" ecore:nsPrefix="_2" ecore:package="org.fpml._2005.fp.ml._4._2" targetNamespace="http://www.fpml.org/2005/FpML-4-2"> <xsd:complexType name="Currency"> <xsd:simpleContent> <xsd:extension base="xsd:normalizedString"> <xsd:attribute name="currencyScheme" type="xsd:anyURI"/> </xsd:extension> </xsd:simpleContent> </xsd:complexType> <xsd:complexType name="IdentifiedCurrency"> <xsd:annotation> <xsd:documentation>Specifies Currency with ID attribute.</xsd:documentation> </xsd:annotation> <xsd:complexContent> <xsd:extension base="_2:Currency"> <xsd:attribute name="id" type="xsd:ID"/> </xsd:extension> </xsd:complexContent> </xsd:complexType> </xsd:schema>
Correct result should be: <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <xsd:schema xmlns:_2="http://www.fpml.org/2005/FpML-4-2" xmlns:ecore="http://www.eclipse.org/emf/2002/Ecore" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" targetNamespace="http://www.fpml.org/2005/FpML-4-2" ecore:nsPrefix="_2" ecore:package="org.fpml._2005.fp.ml._4._2"> <xsd:complexType name="Currency"> <xsd:simpleContent> <xsd:extension base="xsd:normalizedString"> <xsd:attribute name="currencyScheme" type="xsd:anyURI"/> </xsd:extension> </xsd:simpleContent> </xsd:complexType> <xsd:complexType name="IdentifiedCurrency"> <xsd:annotation> <xsd:documentation>Specifies Currency with ID attribute.</xsd:documentation> </xsd:annotation> <xsd:simpleContent> <xsd:extension base="_2:Currency"> <xsd:attribute name="id" type="xsd:ID"/> </xsd:extension> </xsd:simpleContent> </xsd:complexType> </xsd:schema>
This example comes from the latest Maintenance release, incorporating the patch from #155338
Examples will be attached.

Created an attachment (id=48848) The actual, incorrect result
Created an attachment (id=48849) The eCore model generated

Matt,
I believe that the actual result and the expected result are equivalent and both are valid. The part of the specification (XML Representation Summary: complexType Element Information Item) that talks about the properties of a complex type for the case of a complexContent element states the following:
3.2 If the <extension> alternative is chosen, then the appropriate case among the following: 3.2.1 If the effective content is empty, then the {content type} of the type definition resolved to by the actual value of the base [attribute]
This implies that even in the case that we have a complexContent element, if there are no particles specified (effective content is empty), the content type of this type will be that of the base type, which may be simple, as in this case.
Do you have any reference you could point me to that would indicate this result is invalid or specifies a different abstract result? The XSD model itself does not consider this to be invalid, and produces the same abstract result, i.e., a complex type with simple content as its content type.
I'll return it as works for me based on my determination that the current result is valid and correctly specifies the semantic intent.

bug.short_desc: xsd:choice in a xsd:group breaks ecore:featureMap="choices"

long_desc.thetext:
The use of the annotation ecore:featureMap="choices" for a choice within a xsd:group breaks the annotation feature. It produces an invalid schema.
The result is this invalid schema: <xsd:complexType name="Basket"> <xsd:sequence> <xsd:choice maxOccurs="unbounded"> <xsd:element name="basketName" type="_2:BasketName" form="qualified" minOccurs="0" ecore:lowerBound="0"/> <xsd:element name="basketId" type="_2:BasketId" form="qualified" minOccurs="0" ecore:lowerBound="0" ecore:upperBound="-1"/> <xsd:element name="basketId" type="_2:BasketId" form="qualified" minOccurs="0" ecore:lowerBound="0" ecore:name="basketId1" ecore:upperBound="-1"/> </xsd:choice> </xsd:sequence> <xsd:attribute name="id" type="xsd:ID"/> </xsd:complexType>
Examples will be attached.
Created an attachment (id=48852) An example source document. This is a cut-down example.
Created an attachment (id=48853) Resultant invalid schema

Matthew,
While we are trying to ensure that Ecore -> XML Schema -> Ecore is non-lossy, it's definitely the case that in general XML Schema -> Ecore is lossy. This case is a good example of loss of information that can't be fixed without the capabilities being explored in https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=51210, i.e., recording the complete particle structure of the original schema. It's unfortunate that the resulting schema in this case violates the unique particle attribution rule, but there's nothing I can think of to avoid that.
This case should still produce an ecore:featureMap annotation, so I'll fix that. And there are ecore:lowerBound="0" annotations that are redundant with regard to the minOccurs="0" so I'll fix that too.

The fixes has been committed to CVS.
The following would produce a better EMF model:
<xsd:group name="BasketIdentifier.model"> <xsd:sequence> <xsd:element name="basketName" type="BasketName" minOccurs="0"/> <xsd:element name="basketId" type="BasketId" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/> </xsd:sequence> </xsd:group>
It's only different in that the constraint that both basketName and basketId can't be missing is not specified as in the original.

Ed - I understand that XML Schema to eCore is lossy, but should the resultant eCore model still produce an invalid schema? Is producing an invalid XML Schema from eCore using the XSDExporter ever justified? I would expect that the result might be lossy, but still valid.
I tested this and it now complies to the specification by producing an invalid XML Schema.

Matthew,
Something like the unique particle attribute rule is a very sublte constraint that many validators don't check. If one just literally interprets the annotations on the model, and there are duplicate namespace/name features, it's very easy to end up with this result. I.e., any time all the features are optional, and there are duplicates, this will be the result. The mapping for the case of duplicates in the orginal schema is perhaps to blame. It's one of those dark corners that only a complete representation of the original particle structure can enlighten...

solution is to be able to have an xml editor without the design view.

Ctrl+F6 , Ctrl+Shift+F6 , Ctrl+e are the right shortcut keys to switch between editors.

The core issue here is the performance of the Eclipse Core Expressions framework. An evaluation context has to be created for every evaluation, and each object must be evaluated since (even though two objects may have the same time), they may evaluate differently against a core expression based on property testers.
We do cache the evaluation once it's made though, at which point we refer to the cache afterwards.

Caching wise the expression framework could only cache the result of an instanceof expression since its value is fixed over time. Caching this value might help in this particular problem since the instanceof expression accounts for 8% of the time. All other values can't be cache (like you can't cache the value of a global expression in Java).

bug.short_desc: Problems view redefinable default action depending on marker type

long_desc.thetext:
This is actually an issue that appeared in the CDT, and I am trying to come up with a strategy to resolve https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=151005 C compilers may generate error messages for files which are not workspace resources. The CDT error parser generates problem markers for them using the project which was being compiled. Therefore the standard "Go To" action (or, double click) in the Problems view fails: A project cannot be opened in an editor. We would still like to get the file opened, in which the error occurred.
Here is a resolution strategy I would like to put up for discussion:
1) For errors in workspace-external files the CDT defines an extra marker type. The new marker type carries extra attributes which hold information about the external location of the file which contains the error. The CDT error parser generates markers of this type when an error in a workspace-external file is reported by the compiler.
2) For the new marker type a new action is contributed which will evaluate the extra information and open the workspace-external file. This is possible even today by making a popupMenu objectContribution and thus augmenting the problem marker's context menu.
Now here is my issue: The Problems view's default action upon a double click is to open the workspace file that is referenced in the marker. This action cannot be changed. It is all hard-coded in the ProblemView's framework. I would suggest to have the openAction marker-type specific so that the default would be implemented in ActionOpenMarker as it is now, but that for certain marker types a different action could be contributed (via extension point or API)
I think what would make the most sense is an addition to the markerSupport extension point - perhaps we should add something like a markerActionMapping that maps an type to an action.
Another possible way to solve this problem is to fix bug 22284.

(In reply to comment #2) > Another possible way to solve this problem is to fix bug 22284.
Sounds like a silver bullet: Very elegant, but extremely hard to come by. (The bug has been open for years but nobody fixed it) It sure is outside the range of my (CDT) competence.
This is also an issue with a view - we should solve it at the UI level not the core level.

bug.short_desc: [TabbedProperties] Add Context support for Property Contributor

long_desc.thetext:
I suppose that I am probably overlooking a setting that is available on propertyTab or propertySection extension points. But when I start the GMF Logic example editor, my editor's plug-in is activated and the tabbed propertiesBrowserPage attempts to create an instance of one of my PropertySections, or actually, I think it is creating a filter object to ask if it is "enabled". This causes many plug-ins in the workbench to get activated.
The reason I happened to discover this is that my propertysection's filter is throwing an exception (it had compile errors) on instantiation. Another bug should probably be opened to track this, but the tabbed prop framework is not guarded against ill-behaved extensions, or exception. For example, when clicking on the Finish button in the wizard, the wizard dialog won't even close because of the exception caused by my compile error.

Here is a stacktrace section showing the plug-in activation:
EquinoxRegistryStrategy(RegistryStrategyOSGI).createExecutableExtension(RegistryContributor, String, String) line: 157 ExtensionRegistry.createExecutableExtension(RegistryContributor, String, String) line: 759 ConfigurationElement.createExecutableExtension(String) line: 243 ConfigurationElementHandle.createExecutableExtension(String) line: 51 SectionDescriptor.getFilter() line: 146 TabbedPropertyRegistryClassSectionFilter.appliesToSelection(ISectionDescriptor, ISelection) line: 65 SectionDescriptor.appliesTo(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 178 TabbedPropertyRegistry.adaptDescriptorFor(TabDescriptor, IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 270 TabbedPropertyRegistry.filterTabDescriptors(TabDescriptor[], IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 247 TabbedPropertyRegistry.getTabDescriptors(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 234 PropertiesBrowserPage(TabbedPropertySheetPage).setInput(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 656 PropertiesBrowserPage(TabbedPropertySheetPage).selectionChanged(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 525 PropertiesBrowserPage.selectionChanged(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 253 PropertySheet.selectionChanged(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 218 PageSelectionService(AbstractSelectionService).fireSelection(IWorkbenchPart, ISelection) line: 156 PageSelectionService(AbstractSelectionService).setActivePart(IWorkbenchPart) line: 282 WorkbenchPagePartList.fireActivePartChanged(IWorkbenchPartReference, IWorkbenchPartReference) line: 59 WorkbenchPagePartList(PartList).setActivePart(IWorkbenchPartReference) line: 126 WorkbenchPage.setActivePart(IWorkbenchPart) line: 3190
Anthony, can you think of a fix that would be safe enough to be considered for 3.2.1?

Randy, you need to do two things:
The logic editor defines a propertyContributor extension point with a unique ID. Your editor should not have the same ID.
Your filter should be in a separate package and you should make use of the exceptions list in the plug-in manifest so that when the propertySection loads the filter, it does not cause your plug-in to load.
By doing the above, your plug-in will not load when the logic example is started.

(In reply to comment #0) > ... > This causes many plug-ins in the workbench to get activated. > ...
Randy, did you actually observe that many other plug-ins got activated (this is what I read from your description of the problem), or were you speculating that because your plug-ins got activated, many other probably would, too?

OK, I have since found the propertyContributor extension point and this provides one mechanism for grouping the other extension points. Of course, my discovery test case was two clients of GMF. It seems that all GMF-based editors use the same contributor ID: "org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.diagram.ui.properties". GMF's Logic example does not seem to define a propertyContributor extension, nor does my GMF-based editor. I guess this is necessary because they both want to pick up common tabbed pages/sections from GMF.
So, maybe a propertyContributor ID could be an org.eclipse.ui.context. This could allow further refinement of scope. My editor would create a context that extends a default GMF context, and that would be it's propertyContributor's ID.
What happens if I mark my Filter class as special (exceptions list in manifest), but the filter loads other classes from the plug-in that are not on the exceptions list?

> Randy, did you actually observe that many other plug-ins got activated (this is > what I read from your description of the problem), or were you speculating that > because your plug-ins got activated, many other probably would, too?
I saw my plug-in get activated, and it is not related to the GMF example plug-in other than the fact that it also uses GMF. So a more correct, but still unobserved conclusion, might be that most plug-ins which use GMF and define properties extensions will get activated because everyone wanting GMF tabs to appear must use the same contributor ID.

(In reply to comment #5) > What happens if I mark my Filter class as special (exceptions list in > manifest), but the filter loads other classes from the plug-in that are not on > the exceptions list?
From MAINFEST.MF: Eclipse-LazyStart: true; exceptions="myplugin.filterpackage.package"
If myplugin.filterpackage.FilterClass calls myplugin.package.Class, your plug-in is loaded.

I do not understand why this bug was reopened.
This issue is no different than any other Eclipse extension point, unless you put the filter class in the exceptions list, your plug-in is loaded when the class is loaded.
If your filter class causes your plug-in to load since it calls other classes, this is a issue you need to solve in your filter class.
At minimum, it sounds like you should not be using "org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.diagram.ui.properties" and defining your own id. As well, early in your filter class, you should be checking if the selection is in your domain and if not exit.

bug.short_desc: [1.5][compiler] NullPointerException in SourceTypeBinding.initializeDeprecatedAnnotationTagBits():980

long_desc.thetext:
In particular, I get the exception because "this.scope" is null.
Thread [Worker-3] (Suspended (exception NullPointerException)) SourceTypeBinding.initializeDeprecatedAnnotationTagBits() line: 973 SingleTypeReference(ASTNode).isTypeUseDeprecated(TypeBinding, Scope) line: 398 SingleTypeReference(TypeReference).resolveType(ClassScope) line: 160 SingleTypeReference(TypeReference).resolveSuperType(ClassScope) line: 110 ClassScope.findSupertype(TypeReference) line: 1084 ClassScope.connectSuperclass() line: 804 ClassScope.connectTypeHierarchy() line: 929 CompilationUnitScope.connectTypeHierarchy() line: 288 LookupEnvironment.completeTypeBindings() line: 198 LookupEnvironment.completeTypeBindings(CompilationUnitDeclaration) line: 229 CompilationUnitResolver(Compiler).accept(ICompilationUnit, AccessRestriction) line: 306 CompilationUnitResolver.accept(ISourceType[], PackageBinding, AccessRestriction) line: 147 LookupEnvironment.askForType(char[][]) line: 108 UnresolvedReferenceBinding.resolve(LookupEnvironment, boolean) line: 43 BinaryTypeBinding.resolveType(TypeBinding, LookupEnvironment, ParameterizedTypeBinding, int) line: 131 BinaryTypeBinding.resolveTypesFor(MethodBinding) line: 880 BinaryTypeBinding.methods() line: 861 TypeBinding.getDeclaredMethods() line: 200 ...
I originally tracked this down because I was trying to call TypeBinding.getDeclaredMethods(), and it was returning that there were no methods, when I could bring up the corresponding class in an editor and see that there were.
Unfortunately, I can't make a test case, since I'm working with code under NDA.
Could you please provide a test case? Thanks.

At least provide the whole stack trace. It looks like a case where some binding resolution is requested after the environment has been cleaned (no more scopes are available). If you cannot provide the source code on which you are working because of NDA, could you then extract a small test case that would allow us to track it down? Thanks.
I've got a checkout of org.eclipse.jdt.core, and am trying to understand the cause a little better, so I can extract a test case that doesn't use the code under NDA.
Which build ID are you running ?

This appeared on Eclipse 3.2.0 (build M20060629-1905), although it still appeared when I checked out org.eclipse.jdt.core from CVS.
I'm still working to make a standalone test case, but I debugged it to the point where the problem seems related to the fact that the project I'm working on has part of the source code for a jar file that's on the build path. In particular, what's happening is that I'm trying to call getDeclaredMethods() on an ITypeBinding (corresponding to a class from the jar file), and one of the methods refers to a type in one of those source files. That type subclasses another type in a different source file. When I just removed the source code that corresponded to the supertype, I no longer got the NPE.
One other thing that may be a factor is that in our code, we use the batch ASTParser.createASTs() routine to create DOM ASTs for multiple files at once, but these ITypeBindings are actually getting used outside of the calls to the ASTRequestor.acceptAST(). I'm guessing this might be part of the problem too, since I noticed that the scope field for the SourceTypeBinding is null'd there.
Is there some rule that we're breaking about how the ITypeBindings are supposed to be used?

Ah I see now.
Yes, this could definitely be the root cause of the issue. When creating several ASTs, we notify of the individual ASTs in sequence, then shutdown the infrastructure. So beyond the last notification return point, any question to the DOM AST bindings may be doomed, as it lazily will try to compute the information without a valid context anymore.
You should enforce doing all AST manipulation within the ASTRequestor notifications (or accumulate work to do in the last notification).
In 3.3, we want to improve this API to provide clients with more control for the context life cycle; i.e. client should be able to keep the context alive until it is done.

Do calls to ASTParser.createAST() act differently than the batch calls?
The odd thing to me is that I would have expected to run into this problem earlier, since our code has used the batch AST mode in this way for a while.

Quite a few things may work beyond the death of the context, but not everything.
For a single AST creation, the context is not killed at the end. It is discarded by the GC. For multiple ASTs, the context is explicitly discarded at the end of the last notification.
Maxime - is this related to bug 159631 ?

(In reply to comment #9) > Maxime - is this related to bug 159631 ? >
The short answer is most likely no: - this is affecting another code area; - the reason why the scope gets nullified is likely to be different here, since there is an explicit action upon ASTParser.createAST() results that is not bound by the createAST duration, while bug 159631 could be reproduced within createAST invocation.
We could blindly protect against scope being null, but this seems to be extreme... Or else we could reframe this within the API effort you talk about in comment #6.
Scenario to challenge with the new AST pipeline API.
We cannot get the binding environment API in time for 3.3M5 so moving to 3.3M6.
For 3.3, we might want to protect against the NPE.

Feels like overkill if we add null checks everywhere misuse of the compiler internals may occur as a consequence of using this API.
Maybe a global runtimeException catch on the outside would do the trick ? To protect invalid usecase... not convinced this isn't a bad idea anyway.

Closing as dup of bug 164660. I will add logging in this case. The exception is caught inside the getDeclaredMethods() call and we shallow it. We should log it to be sure we don't hide another bug.
